  {
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
      "name": "generate_explanation",
      "description": "Opens a multi-file diff view and generates AI-powered inline comments explaining the changes between two git references. Use this tool to help users understand code changes from git commits, pull requests, branches, or any git refs. The tool uses git to retrieve file contents and displays a side-by-side diff view with explanatory comments.",
      "strict": false,
      "parameters": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "title": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "A descriptive title for the diff view (e.g., 'Changes in commit abc123', 'PR #42: Add authentication', 'Changes between main and feature-branch')"
          },
          "from_ref": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "The git reference for the 'before' state. Can be a commit hash, branch name, tag, or relative reference like HEAD~1, HEAD^, origin/main, etc."
          },
          "to_ref": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "The git reference for the 'after' state. Can be a commit hash, branch name, tag, or relative reference. If not provided, compares to the current working directory (including uncommitted changes)."
          }
        },
        "required": [
          "title",
          "from_ref"
        ],
        "additionalProperties": false
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
      "name": "triggerNordicAction",
      "description": "Execute commands in the nRF Connect terminal (correct NCS SDK environment), OR capture live logs from connected nRF devices.\nUSE action=\"execute\" for ALL NCS CLI (west, nrfjprog, nrfutil). USE action=\"log_device\" ONLY for log capture. NEVER use execute_command for NCS SDK tasks.\n\nCRITICAL OPERATIONAL RULES:\n1. BOARD NAMES: Must be full Zephyr ID (e.g., \"nrf52840dk/nrf52840\", NOT \"nrf52840dk\"). Use for example \"west boards -f \"{name}/{qualifiers}\" | grep nrf52840\" to verify.\n2. BUILD DIRS: User may have custom build dirs (e.g., build_52840, build_central). Use --build-dir (-d) to target them.\n3. MULTI-DEVICE FLASH: Use \"west flash --snr <serial_number>\" to target a specific device. Required when >1 device connected.\n4. PROCESS CLEANUP (run before flash or log capture):\n   - Linux/Mac: pkill -9 JLink && pkill -9 nrfutil\n   - Windows:   cmd /c \"taskkill /F /IM JLink.exe 2>nul & taskkill /F /IM nrfutil.exe 2>nul\"\n     (always wrap in cmd /c — '&' and '2>nul' are cmd.exe syntax, but the user may be in PowerShell, which rejects them; cmd /c \"...\" makes it portable)\n5. PORTS: Windows uses COMx; Linux uses /dev/ttyACMx; Mac uses /dev/tty.usbmodemXXXX.\n6. DEVICE LISTING: For device enumeration, use action=\"log_device\" operation=\"list\". NEVER call nrfutil device list via execute_command directly.\n",
      "strict": false,
      "parameters": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "action": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "The action to perform. Options:\n- \"execute\": Run a west/nrfjprog/nrfutil command in the nRF Connect terminal (correct SDK env). Use for ALL NCS CLI operations.\n- \"log_device\": Run the native Nordic Logger tool. Use ONLY for live UART/RTT log capture."
          },
          "command": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Required if action=\"execute\". The shell command to run in the nRF Connect terminal.\nExamples:\n- \"west boards | grep nrf52840\"      (Find correct board name)\n- \"west build -b nrf52840dk/nrf52840 .\"  (Build)\n- \"west build -d build_52840 --pristine -b nrf52840dk/nrf52840 .\"  (Build with custom dir)\n- \"west flash\"                       (Flash single device)\n- \"west flash --snr 683335182\"       (Flash specific device)\n- \"nrfjprog --recover\"\n- \"nrfutil device list\""
          },
          "operation": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Required if action=\"log_device\". Options: \"list\", \"test\", \"capture\", \"monitor\", \"device_info\".\n- \"list\": List connected nRF devices\n- \"test\": Quick connection test to a device\n- \"capture\": Capture logs for a specified duration and save to file\n- \"monitor\": Continuous live log monitoring (no file save)\n- \"device_info\": Get detailed device information"
          },
          "transport": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Required if action=\"log_device\". Detect from prj.conf:\n- \"uart\": Serial port communication (COM3, /dev/ttyACM0). DEFAULT if not specified.\n- \"rtt\": J-Link RTT (9-digit serial like 683335182). Only if prj.conf shows CONFIG_USE_SEGGER_RTT=y\n\nEXPLICIT RULE: \n✓ User says \"capture UART logs\" → MUST set transport=\"uart\"\n✓ User says \"show logs from RTT\" → MUST set transport=\"rtt\"  \n✓ prj.conf shows CONFIG_LOG_BACKEND_UART=y → set transport=\"uart\"\n✓ prj.conf shows CONFIG_USE_SEGGER_RTT=y → set transport=\"rtt\"\n✓ prj.conf does not show any → set transport=\"uart\" (UART is the default).\n\nIf unsure, tool auto-detects from prj.conf, but ALWAYS pass explicit transport for clarity."
          },
          "port": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Required for \"test\", \"capture\", \"monitor\" (unless \"devices\" is used). \n- For UART: The serial port (e.g. /dev/ttyACM0, COM3, /dev/tty.usbmodem14101).\n- For RTT: The J-Link Serial Number (e.g. 683335182). CRITICAL: NEVER pass a COM port or /dev/tty* port when using RTT. RTT strictly uses 9-12 digit J-Link serial numbers."
          },
          "duration": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"capture\". Recording duration in seconds. \n- Quick test: 5 seconds\n- Boot capture: 15 seconds  \n- Standard: 30 seconds (default)\n- Extended: 60+ seconds\nChoose based on investigation goal."
          },
          "pre-capture-delay": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"capture\". Delay in seconds before device reset (pre-capture listening phase).\n- Use for boot log capture: listeners start BEFORE reset\n- Default: 0 (no delay)\n- Recommended: 2-3 seconds for boot logs\nThis ensures complete boot sequence is captured."
          },
          "devices": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"capture\". Multi-device mapping: \"label:identifier,label2:identifier2\".\nThe label is used to name the output log file. Use generic labels (device1, device2) when roles are unknown.\nUse role-specific labels (central, peripheral) ONLY when the role has been confirmed by project config or log analysis.\n- For UART: identifier is the serial port (e.g. \"device1:/dev/ttyACM0\").\n- For RTT: identifier is the serial number (e.g. \"device1:683335182\"). CRITICAL: NEVER pass a COM port or /dev/tty* port when using RTT. RTT strictly uses 9-12 digit J-Link serial numbers."
          },
          "output": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"capture\". Directory to save logs."
          },
          "reset": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional. Reset device(s) before capture. DEFAULT: true. Set to false ONLY for mid-runtime capture."
          },
          "auto_detect": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional. Auto-detect all connected nRF devices. Set to true for BLE/multi-device scenarios where you want to capture everything without specifying ports."
          },
          "list_nrf": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional. When true with operation=\"list\", shows only nRF devices."
          }
        },
        "required": [
          "action"
        ],
        "additionalProperties": false
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
      "name": "triggerEspAction",
      "description": "Run the ESP-IDF toolchain in a terminal with the ESP-IDF environment sourced for you.\n\nUSE action=\"build\" | \"flash\" for the core cycle, action=\"monitor\" to CAPTURE serial logs/crashes to a file, or action=\"execute\" with a \"command\" for any other idf.py/esptool/python command (including device identification: esptool.py flash_id, idf.py --version, idf.py size).\nNEVER use execute_command for ESP-IDF tasks — a plain terminal has no IDF environment.\n\nCRITICAL OPERATIONAL RULES:\n1. ENVIRONMENT: Never run idf.py/esptool via execute_command. This tool provides the sourced ESP-IDF environment.\n2. DEVICE IDENTITY (run BEFORE the first build/flash, via action=\"execute\"): identify the connected chip and flash so you build for the right target.\n   - \"esptool.py flash_id\"  → chip type + revision + features (WiFi/BLE) + flash (ROM) size in one call.\n   - \"idf.py --version\"      → the ESP-IDF version.\n   - \"python -m serial.tools.list_ports\"  → enumerate serial ports (which board is on which port).\n   - PSRAM is a config fact: read sdkconfig (CONFIG_SPIRAM*), confirmed at runtime by the boot log (\"Found 8MB SPI RAM device\").\n   - \"idf.py size\"  → app IRAM/DRAM/Flash usage (after a build).\n3. TARGET: A project builds for one chip (esp32, esp32s3, esp32c3, esp32c6...). Set it with action=\"execute\" command=\"idf.py set-target esp32s3\" before the first build if it differs from sdkconfig's CONFIG_IDF_TARGET.\n4. PORTS: discover the port ONCE (command=\"python -m serial.tools.list_ports\"), then ALWAYS pass \"port\" to flash and monitor. A portless flash/monitor makes esptool open every serial device (/dev/ttyS0..S31 on Linux) one by one before finding the board, and picks the wrong one when two boards are attached. Linux: /dev/ttyUSB* or /dev/ttyACM*; macOS: /dev/cu.usbserial-* or /dev/cu.usbmodem*; Windows: COMx.\n5. MONITOR = log capture: action=\"monitor\" runs idf.py monitor for \"duration\" seconds and SAVES the serial output (panic backtraces already decoded to file:line) to logs/uart/<name>_<chip>_<port>_<ts>.log. It resets the board first by default (set reset=\"false\" for mid-runtime capture). This is how you capture crashes/coredumps — do NOT run \"idf.py monitor\" via execute (it would hang).\n6. CLEAN/RECONFIG: use action=\"execute\" with command=\"idf.py fullclean\" or \"idf.py reconfigure\" when the build is in a bad state.\n",
      "strict": false,
      "parameters": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "action": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "The ESP-IDF action to perform. Options:\n- \"build\":   Compile the project (idf.py build).\n- \"flash\":   Flash the built firmware to the connected ESP32 (idf.py flash).\n- \"monitor\": Capture the serial console to a log file for \"duration\" seconds, with panic backtraces decoded (wraps idf.py monitor). Use this to capture boot logs, crashes and coredumps.\n- \"execute\": Run any other command in the IDF environment via the \"command\" parameter (idf.py subcommands, esptool.py, python)."
          },
          "command": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Required if action=\"execute\". The FULL command to run in the IDF environment (include the binary name).\nExamples:\n- \"idf.py set-target esp32s3\"          (Select the chip before building)\n- \"idf.py --version\"                   (ESP-IDF version)\n- \"idf.py size\"                        (App Flash/RAM usage, after a build)\n- \"idf.py fullclean\"                   (Wipe the build directory)\n- \"idf.py reconfigure\"                 (Re-run CMake configure)\n- \"esptool.py flash_id\"                (Connected chip type, revision, features, flash size)\n- \"python -m serial.tools.list_ports\"  (Enumerate connected serial ports)"
          },
          "port": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "For \"flash\" and \"monitor\": the serial port of the target board. Discover it once via command=\"python -m serial.tools.list_ports\", then pass it on EVERY flash/monitor (don't rely on auto-detect — it scans all ports and can pick the wrong board).\n- Linux:   /dev/ttyUSB0 or /dev/ttyACM0\n- macOS:   /dev/cu.usbserial-1410 or /dev/cu.usbmodem*\n- Windows: COM5"
          },
          "duration": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"monitor\". Capture duration in seconds (default 10).\n- Crash / boot capture: 10 seconds\n- Connection / Wi-Fi debug: 20-30 seconds\n- Stability test: 60+ seconds"
          },
          "name": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"monitor\". A label used in the log filename (e.g. \"boot\", \"wifi\", \"crash\"). Defaults to the project/chip name."
          },
          "reset": {
            "type": "string",
            "description": "Optional for \"monitor\". Reset the board before capturing (DEFAULT: true — captures the full boot sequence). Set to \"false\" for mid-runtime capture without resetting."
          }
        },
        "required": [
          "action"
        ],
        "additionalProperties": false
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
      "name": "12345670mcp0test_tool",
      "description": "test-server: A test tool",
      "strict": false,
      "parameters": {
